You will have to apply all the knowledge you will receive by that time to answer the questions.

00:56.000 --> 00:59.000
Therefore, I recommend that you be very attentive.

00:59.000 --> 01:03.000
So, the methodologies and technologies.

01:03.000 --> 01:09.000
When using different technologies of assessing personnel, those that we have considered,

01:09.000 --> 01:14.000
different private specific methods can be used.

01:15.000 --> 01:17.000
I would divide them into three groups.

01:17.000 --> 01:20.000
The first is the methodology of assessing the work of a person.

01:20.000 --> 01:25.000
The second is the methodology of assessing the knowledge of qualifications and competences.

01:25.000 --> 01:30.000
And the third is the quantitative assessment of the quality indicators of behavior.

01:30.000 --> 01:35.000
The last one is probably the most complex, but I think we will figure it out.

01:35.000 --> 01:39.000
Let's start with the methodology of assessing the work of a person.

01:40.000 --> 01:49.000
Let's start with the fact that there are four principles according to which we can assess the work.

01:49.000 --> 01:56.000
And violation of these principles usually leads to failure in our entire assessment of personnel.

01:56.000 --> 01:58.000
So, the first one.

01:58.000 --> 02:01.000
We have to choose the correct indicators.

02:01.000 --> 02:04.000
And it is very easy to choose the wrong ones.

02:04.000 --> 02:09.000
We will see later which indicators are correct and which are not.

02:09.000 --> 02:14.000
When choosing indicators, we should also keep in mind that they can be absolute or relative.

02:14.000 --> 02:19.000
The absolute one is, for example, 648 something.

02:19.000 --> 02:25.000
A kilogram, a thousand dollars, kilometers of the path.

02:25.000 --> 02:28.000
And it can be relative.

02:28.000 --> 02:31.000
For example, 15% of something.

02:31.000 --> 02:38.000
From the plan, or from what the unit has done in general, or from what the best worker of the unit does.

02:38.000 --> 02:40.000
It is not so important.

02:40.000 --> 02:46.000
In fact, we should well imagine that in some cases absolute indicators are important for us, and in others relative.

02:46.000 --> 02:49.000
We will deal with this a little later.

02:49.000 --> 02:55.000
The second important point is the choice of representative intervals of time.

02:55.000 --> 03:00.000
Tell me, please, is it possible to assess the work of a manager,

03:00.000 --> 03:04.000
under the leadership of which there are 8 people, in one day?

03:04.000 --> 03:06.000
I'm afraid it's difficult, right?

03:06.000 --> 03:08.000
And in two days?

03:08.000 --> 03:10.000
And in a month?

03:10.000 --> 03:11.000
And in a quarter?

03:11.000 --> 03:13.000
And in a year?

03:13.000 --> 03:16.000
In short, there are such intervals of time,

03:16.000 --> 03:24.000
during which we have criteria to assess the work as the best or the worst.

03:24.000 --> 03:29.000
At larger intervals of time it doesn't make sense.

03:29.000 --> 03:33.000
At smaller intervals of time we simply won't see what's going on.

03:33.000 --> 03:39.000
The third, the analysis of the dynamics of human work over time is extremely important.

03:39.000 --> 03:41.000
We have already talked a little about this.

03:42.000 --> 03:46.000
It is very important for us to understand not only how he is now,

03:46.000 --> 03:52.000
but whether his indicators are improving or deteriorating, or remain the same.

03:52.000 --> 03:55.000
This is one of the goals of our assessment,

03:55.000 --> 03:59.000
to predict what a person will do next,

03:59.000 --> 04:02.000
and to do this we need to understand in which direction the trend is developing.

04:02.000 --> 04:09.000
And finally, an extremely important point is the account of the influence of so-called external factors,

04:09.000 --> 04:15.000
that is, those factors that can be assessed, their influence can be seen,

04:15.000 --> 04:20.000
but they do not reflect the indicators of human work in any way,

04:20.000 --> 04:26.000
and do not give us any special grounds to assess this work in a positive or negative direction.

04:26.000 --> 04:30.000
How can we choose the indicators that will be correct?

04:30.000 --> 04:33.000
The indicators must correspond to the nature of human work,

04:33.000 --> 04:39.000
that is, they must reflect exactly what we can assess as a good or bad worker, or average,

04:39.000 --> 04:41.000
and not something else.

04:41.000 --> 04:47.000
The second point is that the indicators for different jobs, for different workers,

04:47.000 --> 04:49.000
must be comparable to each other.

04:49.000 --> 04:54.000
If we measure the indicators for one worker in one unit,

04:54.000 --> 04:57.000
for another in a completely different one,

04:57.000 --> 04:59.000
and we cannot compare them with each other,

04:59.000 --> 05:03.000
how can we measure the effectiveness and assess the work?

05:03.000 --> 05:09.000
In other words, the method of comparison must be provided.

05:09.000 --> 05:14.000
The third point is the reflection of the capabilities of the worker himself.

05:14.000 --> 05:16.000
What do I mean?

05:16.000 --> 05:22.000
We must assess the indicators that reflect what a person is able to influence.

05:22.000 --> 05:26.000
If he is not able to influence, then, I'm sorry,

05:26.000 --> 05:31.000
we will hardly get anything correct and can judge his work.

05:31.000 --> 05:34.000
Let's imagine a very simple example.

05:34.000 --> 05:39.000
Let's say we have two shopping centers that sell cell phones.

05:39.000 --> 05:42.000
But one of these shopping centers is located somewhere far away,

05:42.000 --> 05:46.000
on the periphery, in the back yards of a small residential block,

05:46.000 --> 05:51.000
and the other is located near the subway, where a large number of people pass.

05:51.000 --> 05:54.000
Which one do you think will bring more profit?

05:54.000 --> 05:56.000
Obviously, the second one.

05:56.000 --> 05:58.000
It's just better located.

05:58.000 --> 06:01.000
Can this serve as an indicator of the quality of the work of the employees?

06:01.000 --> 06:03.000
No way.

06:03.000 --> 06:06.000
The next question that often raises doubts,

06:06.000 --> 06:09.000
and which is also quite intriguing,

06:09.000 --> 06:12.000
as is the case with most of the issues related to the assessment of the staff,

06:12.000 --> 06:17.000
is the correspondence of indicators that we use in the interests of the enterprise.

06:18.000 --> 06:23.000
You may ask, how can the indicators of the work not correspond to the interests of the enterprise?

06:23.000 --> 06:25.000
It's very simple.

06:25.000 --> 06:32.000
We want the employee in the shopping center to bring as much profit as possible to the enterprise.

06:32.000 --> 06:37.000
And therefore, as the main indicator of his work,

06:37.000 --> 06:40.000
we set the sales volume,

06:40.000 --> 06:44.000
how much money he sold for a certain time,

06:44.000 --> 06:47.000
for example, in a week or a month.

06:47.000 --> 06:49.000
What do we get as a result?

06:49.000 --> 06:53.000
All our managers of the shopping center will run after those buyers

06:53.000 --> 06:56.000
who want to buy a refrigerator, or a TV, or a computer,

06:56.000 --> 07:02.000
but they are absolutely not interested in those visitors who want to buy a mouse for a vacuum cleaner,

07:02.000 --> 07:04.000
or something cheap.

07:04.000 --> 07:07.000
They will run after such buyers,

07:07.000 --> 07:09.000
not pay attention to them,

07:09.000 --> 07:13.000
excuse me for the expression, but will not go to our store.

07:13.000 --> 07:17.000
Does this behavior of the seller correspond to the interests of our company?

07:17.000 --> 07:19.000
Of course, it does not.

07:19.000 --> 07:21.000
Why is it so?

07:21.000 --> 07:23.000
And we have created such an indicator.

07:23.000 --> 07:27.000
So, every time we have to set such indicators of work

07:27.000 --> 07:30.000
that would meet the interests of our company as a whole.

07:30.000 --> 07:33.000
In brackets, I note that the KPI system is optimal for this,

07:33.000 --> 07:38.000
but we remember that its application is associated with certain difficulties.

07:38.000 --> 07:43.000
And finally, there is such a criterion as reasonable sufficiency.

07:43.000 --> 07:45.000
What does it mean?

07:45.000 --> 07:49.000
People with an engineering and technical approach usually think

07:49.000 --> 07:53.000
that the more different indicators we introduce,

07:53.000 --> 07:57.000
the more accurately we will evaluate the work of a person.

07:57.000 --> 07:59.000
This is not so.

07:59.000 --> 08:04.000
As you know, there is a magic number 7 plus minus 2.

08:05.000 --> 08:08.000
This is the volume of human attention,

08:08.000 --> 08:10.000
the volume of short-term memory,

08:10.000 --> 08:13.000
and the so-called control norm.

08:13.000 --> 08:16.000
Due to its psychological features,

08:16.000 --> 08:23.000
a person is not able to evaluate and control more than 5, 7 plus minus 2 objects.

08:23.000 --> 08:29.000
If we introduce an evaluation system of 15, 20, 30 indicators,

08:30.000 --> 08:35.000
it means that we cannot say anything special about these indicators.

08:35.000 --> 08:39.000
Although we have evaluated everything from all sides,

08:39.000 --> 08:43.000
it turns out that some indicators are worse than others,

08:43.000 --> 08:45.000
according to the law of large numbers.

08:45.000 --> 08:47.000
And what happens as a result?

08:47.000 --> 08:49.000
All our employees are about the same.

08:49.000 --> 08:52.000
So, we need to introduce only those key indicators

08:52.000 --> 08:57.000
that really allow us to say whether a person works well or not.

08:57.000 --> 09:00.000
We are not interested in all other indicators.

09:00.000 --> 09:05.000
And we do not need to multiply super-measures.

09:05.000 --> 09:09.000
To better understand what has just been said,

09:09.000 --> 09:11.000
let's look at two examples.

09:11.000 --> 09:13.000
Example number 1.

09:13.000 --> 09:17.000
Imagine a woman who works as a cashier,

09:17.000 --> 09:20.000
and now they are called the owners of the cash register,

09:20.000 --> 09:22.000
in a huge supermarket.

09:23.000 --> 09:27.000
So, customers come to her with their carts full of goods.

09:27.000 --> 09:31.000
And we have a task to ensure career growth,

09:31.000 --> 09:34.000
to select the best,

09:34.000 --> 09:39.000
to make the system of labor payment transparent and tied to the results,

09:39.000 --> 09:43.000
and to evaluate the work of these cash registers.

09:43.000 --> 09:46.000
What indicators can we choose for this?

09:46.000 --> 09:51.000
Let's take such an indicator as the number of serviced customers.

09:51.000 --> 09:53.000
What does it reflect?

09:53.000 --> 09:57.000
It seems to reflect the work of our cash register owner.

09:57.000 --> 10:01.000
But imagine that one of them missed 50 customers,

10:01.000 --> 10:06.000
each of whom had matches and a bottle of kefir in his cart.

10:06.000 --> 10:09.000
And the second one missed only 5 people,

10:09.000 --> 10:13.000
but they had overloaded carts full of goods.

10:13.000 --> 10:18.000
And each of these customers brought us a profit,

10:18.000 --> 10:24.000
let's say, 300 times more than the number of matches, matches and kefir.

10:24.000 --> 10:28.000
Then a good indicator would be the volume of revenue

10:28.000 --> 10:30.000
that passes through the cash register.

10:30.000 --> 10:32.000
But again, it doesn't work.

10:32.000 --> 10:33.000
It's very simple.

10:33.000 --> 10:36.000
How do you think, will a cash register owner influence

10:36.000 --> 10:42.000
how much and what goods a particular customer will put in his cart?

10:42.000 --> 10:43.000
No.

10:43.000 --> 10:45.000
He will sit at the cash register,

10:45.000 --> 10:47.000
he is not a merchandiser,

10:47.000 --> 10:49.000
he does not advertise any goods,

10:49.000 --> 10:51.000
he just checks.

10:51.000 --> 10:56.000
So, these indicators cannot reflect the quality of his work,

10:56.000 --> 11:00.000
simply because it does not affect them in any way.

11:00.000 --> 11:04.000
Let's remember the principle of the correlation of the indicators of work

11:04.000 --> 11:07.000
and the capabilities of our worker.

11:07.000 --> 11:11.000
In many cases, in such stores,

11:11.000 --> 11:13.000
in such large supermarkets,

11:13.000 --> 11:15.000
there are advertising promotions.

11:15.000 --> 11:19.000
Certain goods are promoted,

11:19.000 --> 11:22.000
these goods become priority,

11:22.000 --> 11:25.000
suppliers want to sell more of them.

11:25.000 --> 11:27.000
Maybe this is a new product,

11:27.000 --> 11:33.000
maybe this is a propaganda and development of the store's sales brand.

11:33.000 --> 11:36.000
So, there is such a thing as a priority product,

11:36.000 --> 11:39.000
the one that would be good to be sold more.

11:39.000 --> 11:43.000
Can we assess the work of our cash register

11:43.000 --> 11:47.000
through the quantity or quality of the sold priority goods?

11:47.000 --> 11:48.000
No.

11:48.000 --> 11:51.000
It will not run around the shopping mall.

11:51.000 --> 11:54.000
The maximum it can do is to check,

11:54.000 --> 11:57.000
to be interested or to offer to buy a particular product.

11:57.000 --> 11:59.000
But then we will complicate its work.

11:59.000 --> 12:01.000
We will have queues,

12:01.000 --> 12:02.000
and this is good,

12:02.000 --> 12:03.000
no, this is bad,

12:03.000 --> 12:04.000
we do not like it.

12:04.000 --> 12:06.000
This will cause indignation of the customers.

12:06.000 --> 12:10.000
So, three indicators that seem to be very good

12:10.000 --> 12:12.000
and reflect the work of cash registers

12:12.000 --> 12:15.000
are not really suitable for our criteria.

12:15.000 --> 12:17.000
And what is suitable?

12:17.000 --> 12:21.000
It turns out that there are only two indicators.

12:21.000 --> 12:26.000
The first is the number of released or scanned goods per unit of time.

12:26.000 --> 12:31.000
One cash registerer scans 3,000 goods per shift,

12:31.000 --> 12:34.000
and the other, let's say, 15,000.

12:34.000 --> 12:37.000
This means that one cash register works very fast,

12:37.000 --> 12:39.000
performs its function,

12:39.000 --> 12:41.000
therefore, it quickly lets the buyers through,

12:41.000 --> 12:43.000
it does not create queues.

12:43.000 --> 12:46.000
This is a good indicator.

12:46.000 --> 12:48.000
This is a much better indicator

12:48.000 --> 12:53.000
than the number of missed buyers,

12:53.000 --> 12:55.000
which our cash register does not affect,

12:55.000 --> 12:58.000
or the indicator of the volume of the proceeds through the cash register,

12:58.000 --> 13:00.000
which it also does not affect.

13:00.000 --> 13:01.000
It affects only one thing.

13:02.000 --> 13:05.000
How many times does it scan goods per unit of time?

13:05.000 --> 13:07.000
Is this enough? No, it is not.

13:07.000 --> 13:10.000
Because it is also very important for us

13:10.000 --> 13:12.000
how many mistakes it makes.

13:12.000 --> 13:15.000
How many times does it ask the senior cash registerer

13:15.000 --> 13:17.000
to come to it with a key and scan a check?

13:17.000 --> 13:19.000
Because it has missed twice,

13:19.000 --> 13:21.000
missed, missed again,

13:21.000 --> 13:25.000
it starts a gentle and affectionate conversation with the buyer,

13:25.000 --> 13:27.000
who is tired of all this.

13:27.000 --> 13:30.000
This means that this number of mistakes should also be taken into account.

13:31.000 --> 13:35.000
These are two indicators that more or less correspond to our criteria.

13:35.000 --> 13:37.000
Agree, they are slightly less obvious

13:37.000 --> 13:41.000
than the indicators that we considered as incorrect.

13:41.000 --> 13:47.000
Now, let's go to the shopping hall of our store.

13:47.000 --> 13:51.000
Let's assume that we are going to implement

13:51.000 --> 13:53.000
a fairly complex household appliance,

13:53.000 --> 13:55.000
electrical appliances,

13:55.000 --> 13:57.000
fridges, TVs,

13:57.000 --> 13:59.000
video cameras, and so on.

14:01.000 --> 14:03.000
And in our hall there are managers

14:03.000 --> 14:05.000
who have to work with the buyer,

14:05.000 --> 14:07.000
explain what he buys,

14:07.000 --> 14:09.000
why he buys it,

14:09.000 --> 14:11.000
why it is so expensive,

14:11.000 --> 14:13.000
recommend, show, and so on.

14:13.000 --> 14:15.000
This is its function.

14:15.000 --> 14:18.000
We want this from the manager in the shopping hall.

14:18.000 --> 14:20.000
Or a sales consultant, as they are also called.

14:21.000 --> 14:26.000
Let's try to introduce two indicators into their work.

14:26.000 --> 14:29.000
The first one is the number of goods that they have missed.

14:29.000 --> 14:33.000
For example, he missed 30 units during the shift.

14:33.000 --> 14:36.000
This is better than if he missed 10 units.

14:36.000 --> 14:38.000
Three times.

14:38.000 --> 14:42.000
And we are also very interested in the volume of his sales.

14:43.000 --> 14:51.000
The one who missed goods for, let's say, 500,000 rubles

14:51.000 --> 14:56.000
is, of course, five times better than the one who missed 100,000 rubles.

14:58.000 --> 15:00.000
These are good indicators.

15:00.000 --> 15:03.000
At first glance, it seems that they are quite relevant

15:03.000 --> 15:05.000
and meet our tasks, and so on.

15:05.000 --> 15:07.000
But let's see.

15:07.000 --> 15:11.000
The number of goods and the volume of sales

15:11.000 --> 15:16.000
are they only dependent on the work of our respected consultant?

15:18.000 --> 15:19.000
No.

15:19.000 --> 15:22.000
They depend on where our shopping mall is located.

15:22.000 --> 15:25.000
How popular is the brand of your store?

15:25.000 --> 15:27.000
How well-known is it?

15:27.000 --> 15:29.000
How convenient is its location?

15:29.000 --> 15:32.000
In the end, it depends on the time of year.

15:32.000 --> 15:36.000
Is it before the New Year, when everyone runs to buy gifts?

15:36.000 --> 15:40.000
Or after the New Year, when we experience the consequences

15:40.000 --> 15:44.000
of what we bought and used during the New Year holidays?

15:44.000 --> 15:51.000
These are two indicators that somehow reflect the work of our sales consultant

15:51.000 --> 15:53.000
or manager of the shopping mall.

15:53.000 --> 15:57.000
But it may turn out that these indicators work against us.

15:57.000 --> 16:02.000
That is, the principle of compliance with the interests of our enterprise is violated.

16:02.000 --> 16:07.000
Let's say we set our consultant's work evaluation criteria

16:08.000 --> 16:11.000
as the volume of sales.

16:11.000 --> 16:16.000
That is, how many rubles did he sell in two shifts per week?

16:16.000 --> 16:18.000
An interesting question.

16:18.000 --> 16:22.000
As soon as we do this, our respected consultants will start running

16:22.000 --> 16:25.000
after buyers who want to buy expensive goods

16:25.000 --> 16:29.000
and ignore those who want to buy something cheap.

16:29.000 --> 16:32.000
There are many such examples.

16:32.000 --> 16:36.000
Thus, we stimulate the behavior of our employees

16:36.000 --> 16:40.000
so that they work against the interests of our enterprise.

16:40.000 --> 16:43.000
What indicators can be correct?

16:43.000 --> 16:47.000
First, we will have to introduce such a useful and very important thing as standards,

16:47.000 --> 16:49.000
that is, plans.

16:49.000 --> 16:51.000
Plans can be set in different ways,

16:51.000 --> 16:55.000
but it is best to set them based on the specifics of the location

16:55.000 --> 16:59.000
and other characteristics of our given shopping mall.

16:59.000 --> 17:04.000
If we evaluate the enterprises in a favorable or unfavorable zone

17:04.000 --> 17:07.000
based on the same indicators,

17:07.000 --> 17:10.000
or if some other factors influence them,

17:10.000 --> 17:13.000
most likely some of them will be bad all the time,

17:13.000 --> 17:15.000
and others will be good all the time.

17:15.000 --> 17:17.000
Let's make it easier.

17:17.000 --> 17:19.000
Let's set different plans.

17:19.000 --> 17:23.000
We will evaluate a person based on whether he has fulfilled this plan or not.

17:23.000 --> 17:27.000
In addition, we will remember the principle of compliance with human capabilities.

17:27.000 --> 17:31.000
If one of our sales consultants is a beginner and has only been working for a month,

17:31.000 --> 17:35.000
and the other is an old Zubr who has been here for 4 years and knows everything perfectly,

17:35.000 --> 17:37.000
and knows everything perfectly,

17:37.000 --> 17:39.000
and has passed training, and so on,

17:39.000 --> 17:42.000
then, of course, the second one will be more effective.

17:42.000 --> 17:44.000
So we need to set a different plan.

17:44.000 --> 17:47.000
But we will notice that the reward system is also important.

17:47.000 --> 17:50.000
What about the sales of priority goods?

17:50.000 --> 17:53.000
When we discussed the owner of the cash register or cashier,

17:53.000 --> 17:57.000
we found out that she does not influence these sales in any special way.

17:57.000 --> 18:01.000
And the consultant is in his hands.

18:01.000 --> 18:05.000
He can advise to buy a brand that is not very well known,

18:05.000 --> 18:07.000
not very popular yet.

18:07.000 --> 18:10.000
He can explain why this particular product is worth buying,

18:10.000 --> 18:12.000
what are its consumer properties.

18:12.000 --> 18:15.000
He can talk to our customer clearly.

18:15.000 --> 18:18.000
So this criterion will also be correct for him.

18:19.000 --> 18:23.000
Speaking about the work of a sales consultant in a trading room,

18:23.000 --> 18:29.000
we have touched on the question of how long it should be to evaluate his work.

18:29.000 --> 18:32.000
For a shift, for a week, for a month.

18:32.000 --> 18:36.000
It seems to me that it is quite difficult to evaluate during a shift.

18:36.000 --> 18:39.000
It is such a small interval for assessment.

18:39.000 --> 18:43.000
Now we will look at an example that clearly shows

18:43.000 --> 18:47.000
how to choose a representative interval for assessment.

18:47.000 --> 18:49.000
Let's take a sales manager,

18:49.000 --> 18:52.000
but he does not work in a supermarket,

18:52.000 --> 18:56.000
but in a company or a company in a trading house.

18:56.000 --> 19:04.000
He sells industrial goods, food, clothing, TNP in large quantities.

19:04.000 --> 19:07.000
He can sell it to end consumers,

19:07.000 --> 19:13.000
to production enterprises that use this product for their own production.

19:13.000 --> 19:18.000
Or he can sell it to small wholesalers or retailers.

19:18.000 --> 19:23.000
We will not even consider what criteria we evaluate its effectiveness.

